window.TEST_DATA = {
"1": {"questext": "In his presidential address to the Muslim League on 29th December 1930, Allama Iqbal called for the amalgamation of which regions into a single North-West Muslim-majority Indian state?", "options": ["Punjab, North-West Frontier Province, Sind and Baluchistan", "Bengal, Assam, Bihar and Orissa", "Punjab, Kashmir, Sindh and Gujarat", "Bombay, Sindh, Punjab and Rajputana"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Punjab, North-West Frontier Province, Sind and Baluchistan.</b><br><br>In his presidential address of 29th December, 1930 to the annual session of the Muslim League, <b>Allama Iqbal</b> called for the amalgamation of the North-West Muslim-majority Indian states consisting of these four regions.<br><br>Poet and political thinker <b>Muhammad Iqbal</b> is often considered the originator of the idea of a separate nation for Muslims. Inspired by the spirit of <b>Pan-Islam</b>, he propounded the theory of '<b>two nations</b>' at the <b>Allahabad session of the League in 1930</b>. It was for the first time that the demand for a separate homeland for Muslims was put forward.", "expimage": ""},
"2": {"questext": "Who coined the specific idea and name 'Pakistan', including its geographical demarcations, in the pamphlet 'Now or Never'?", "options": ["Chaudhary Rahmat Ali", "Allama Iqbal", "Fazlul Haq", "Sikandar Hayat Khan"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Chaudhary Rahmat Ali.</b><br><br><b>Chaudhary Rahmat Ali</b>, a Cambridge student, coined the more specific idea of Pakistan, including its geographical demarcations and the name itself, in his pamphlet <b>'Now or Never'</b>.<br><br>He used it as an acronym referring to the names of five northern regions of the Indian sub-continent under British rule: <br>• Punjab<br>• Afghania/North West Frontier Province<br>• Kashmir<br>• Sindh<br>• Baluchistan<br><br><b>Fazlul Haq</b> and <b>Sikandar Hayat Khan</b> played an important role in drafting this proposal.", "expimage": ""},
"3": {"questext": "What gave Jinnah a 'sense of urgency' and drove his shift towards the demand for a separate Muslim nation, culminating in the 'Two Nation Theory'?", "options": ["Reverses faced by the Muslim League even on Muslim-majority seats in the 1937 elections", "Gandhi's Salt March", "The Simon Commission boycott", "Failure of the Round Table Conference"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Reverses faced by the Muslim League even on Muslim-majority seats in the 1937 elections.</b><br><br>The setbacks faced by the Muslim League in the <b>elections of 1937</b>, even in constituencies where Muslims were in a majority, gave a sense of urgency to <b>Jinnah</b>. He blamed <b>Gandhi and Congress</b> for trying to impose Hinduism in the garb of independence from the British, and his position drifted to the extreme, leading him to demand a separate land for Muslims. This came to be called the <b>'Two Nation Theory'</b>.<br><br>On <b>23/24 March 1940</b>, the '<b>Pakistan Resolution</b>' was passed at the <b>Lahore session</b> of the Muslim League, presided over by Jinnah. On <b>23 March 1943</b>, '<b>Pakistan Day</b>' was celebrated by the League.", "expimage": ""},
"4": {"questext": "Which combination of factors helped the Muslim League gain sympathy and consolidate its demands during the Second World War, despite the rejection of its ideas in the 1937 elections?", "options": ["Absence of Congress leadership after resignation/arrest, and British support under the policy of Divide and Rule", "An active Congress campaign in favour of the League", "Direct financial support from the United States", "The formation of the Indian National Army"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Absence of Congress leadership after resignation/arrest, and British support under the policy of Divide and Rule.</b><br><br>The <b>Second World War</b> came at the most opportune moment for the Muslim League. Though people had rejected its ideas in the 1937 election, its support grew significantly after 1939.<br><br>The <b>absence of Congress leadership</b>, after it had resigned and its leaders were later arrested, contributed to vacating space for the League. The <b>British</b> also found it convenient to support the League as it suited their policy of <b>Divide and Rule</b>, especially since they needed an ally in India during the war.", "expimage": ""},
"5": {"questext": "The Second World War broke out in September 1939. How was India drawn into it?", "options": ["India was involved without any consultation or consent of the Indian people, leading to strong Congress opposition", "India voluntarily joined after a Congress resolution", "India joined only after the Quit India Movement", "India was neutral throughout the war"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>India was involved without any consultation or consent of the Indian people, leading to strong Congress opposition.</b><br><br>The <b>Second World War</b> broke out in <b>September 1939</b> and lasted almost till the latter part of 1945. India, being part of the British Colonial Empire, was involved in the war without any consultation and consent of the Indian people, which led to <b>strong opposition from the Congress</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"6": {"questext": "What approach did Subhash Chandra Bose adopt in response to the opportunity presented by the Second World War?", "options": ["He escaped to Berlin and later Tokyo, and launched the Indian National Army to snatch India's freedom", "He fully cooperated with the British war effort", "He joined Gandhi's Individual Satyagraha", "He led the Quit India Movement from within India"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>He escaped to Berlin and later Tokyo, and launched the Indian National Army to snatch India's freedom.</b><br><br><b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b> wanted to use the opportunity of the war to launch a mass movement to demand or otherwise snatch India's freedom from a weakened England. He believed that '<b>Britain's crisis was an opportunity for India</b>'. He therefore escaped to <b>Berlin</b>, from where he went to <b>Tokyo</b> and later launched the <b>Indian National Army</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"7": {"questext": "What was Gandhi and Nehru's stance towards Britain during the early years of the Second World War?", "options": ["They found it morally wrong to pressure Britain during its fight against Fascism and Nazism, yet remained skeptical of supporting the British Government", "They fully and unconditionally supported the British war effort", "They supported Bose's plan to seek Axis help", "They boycotted all political activity during the war"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>They found it morally wrong to pressure Britain during its fight against Fascism and Nazism, yet remained skeptical of supporting the British Government.</b><br><br><b>Gandhi and Nehru</b> did not find it morally right to exert pressure upon England when it was involved in war efforts against Fascism and Nazism, which they considered morally incorrect, though they were skeptical of providing any support to the British Government.<br><br><b>Nehru</b> made a sharp distinction between <b>Democracy and Fascism</b>. He believed that justice was on the side of <b>Britain, France and Poland</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"8": {"questext": "What conditions did the Congress Working Committee and AICC lay down in their resolution of 10 October 1939 for offering conditional support to the British war effort?", "options": ["That India be declared independent, with a provisional National Government set up and a Constituent Assembly elected on adult suffrage to frame the constitution", "Unconditional support similar to that of the Hindu Mahasabha", "Support only if a separate Muslim nation was created", "Support only if the United States intervened directly"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>That India be declared independent, with a provisional National Government set up and a Constituent Assembly elected on adult suffrage to frame the constitution.</b><br><br>The Congress affirmed its opposition to India's participation in an imperialist war and declared that issues of war and peace were to be decided by the Indian people. On <b>10 October 1939</b>, the <b>Congress Working Committee and the AICC</b> passed a resolution offering conditional support on the condition that <b>India must be declared an independent nation</b>, with a provisional National Government set up and independence granted after the war, and that only the people, through a <b>Constituent Assembly elected on adult suffrage</b>, could shape their own constitution. The <b>Ramgarh session (1940)</b> of the Congress passed a similar resolution.", "expimage": ""},
"9": {"questext": "Which organisation offered unconditional support to the British Government at the outset of the Second World War?", "options": ["Hindu Mahasabha", "Indian National Congress", "Muslim League", "Forward Bloc"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Hindu Mahasabha.</b><br><br>The <b>Hindu Mahasabha</b> offered <b>unconditional support</b> to the British Government during the war. The <b>Muslim League</b>, which dominated the ministries in <b>Punjab, Sindh and Bengal</b>, promised full support to Britain. The <b>Communist Party of India (CPI)</b> also supported the British war effort once Germany attacked Russia, and criticized the Congress for opposing the British.", "expimage": ""},
"10": {"questext": "What prompted the United States to pressure Britain to resolve the Indian problem, ultimately leading to the Cripps Mission?", "options": ["Japan's alarming victories in Southeast Asia and its attack on the US Naval Base at Pearl Harbour", "Direct Action Day riots", "The Royal Indian Navy Mutiny", "The Quit India Movement"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Japan's alarming victories in Southeast Asia and its attack on the US Naval Base at Pearl Harbour.</b><br><br>The alarming victories of Japan in Southeast Asia and the Japanese attack on the US Naval Base '<b>Pearl Harbour</b>' prompted the US to enter the Second World War as a British ally. The US then exerted pressure on Britain to resolve the Indian problem, which led to the onset of the <b>Cripps Mission</b> to India.", "expimage": ""},
"11": {"questext": "The fall of which territories to Japanese forces brought the Second World War to India's doorstep and alarmed Gandhi about a Japanese invasion?", "options": ["Malaya, Singapore, Burma, and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands", "Ceylon and Ladakh", "Tibet and Nepal", "Goa and Daman"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Malaya, Singapore, Burma, and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.</b><br><br>With the fall of <b>Malaya, Singapore, Burma and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands</b> to Japanese forces, the Second World War came to the doorsteps of India. Gandhi observed that the British presence in India was an invitation to Japan to invade, and it was due to the arrival of Japanese forces near India's boundaries that Gandhi called on the British to <b>Quit India</b>.<br><br>The war also brought <b>economic misery</b> to the Indian people through chronic scarcity of essential commodities and a tremendous rise in prices owing to <b>hoarding and black marketing</b>. The Muslim League capitalized on this situation to launch and consolidate the <b>'Pakistan Movement'</b> while supporting the British war effort.", "expimage": ""},
"12": {"questext": "What proposal did the Congress place before the British Government at its Ramgarh session held on 25 March 1940, following a constitutional deadlock caused by the resignation of Congress ministries?", "options": ["That an interim government should be formed at the centre", "The demand for a separate Pakistan", "The Quit India resolution", "A boycott of the Second World War entirely"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>That an interim government should be formed at the centre.</b><br><br>After the resignation of the Congress ministries in the provinces, there was a <b>constitutional deadlock</b> due to Congress' opposition to India's unilateral involvement in the war. At the annual session held at <b>Ramgarh (then Bihar) on 25 March 1940</b>, a proposal was placed before the British government that an <b>interim government should be formed at the centre</b>.<br><br><b>Lord Linlithgow</b> put forward a counter-proposal, named the '<b>August Proposal</b>', demanding formation of an interim government, but this was rejected by the Congress.", "expimage": ""},
"13": {"questext": "Which of the following was NOT among the major proposals of the August Offer (8 August 1940)?", "options": ["Immediate grant of complete independence to India", "Expansion of the Viceroy's Executive Council by enlarging Indian representation", "Establishment of a War Advisory Council of British India and the Princely states", "A representative constitution-making body to decide the constitution after the war"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Immediate grant of complete independence to India was NOT part of the August Offer.</b><br><br>The <b>August Offer</b> of 8 August 1940 had the following major proposals:<br>• An immediate expansion of the <b>Viceroy's Executive Council</b> by enlarging Indian representation.<br>• Establishing a <b>War Advisory Council</b> consisting of representatives of British India and the Princely states.<br>• A representative <b>constitution-making body</b> after the War, where mainly Indians would decide the constitution.<br>• This was subject to fulfilment of Government obligations regarding defence, minority rights, treaties with states and all-India services.<br>• No future constitution was to be adopted without the consent of minorities.<br><br>It did not, however, promise immediate independence.", "expimage": ""},
"14": {"questext": "Who described the dominion status concept, offered under the August Offer, as being 'dead as a rusty door nail'?", "options": ["Jawaharlal Nehru", "Mahatma Gandhi", "M.A. Jinnah", "Dr. Rajendra Prasad"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Jawaharlal Nehru.</b><br><br>The <b>August Offer</b> fell short of Congress demands because it was based on <b>dominion status</b>, which the Congress felt was a totally dead issue, and it did not concede the demand for complete independence now with independence granted after the war. <b>Nehru</b> remarked, \"<b>Dominion status concept is dead as a rusty door nail.</b>\"<br><br><b>Gandhi</b> said the declaration had widened the gulf between the nationalists and British rulers. The <b>Congress rejected</b> the offer, and the <b>Muslim League</b> also rejected it since the demand for Pakistan was not clearly accepted.", "expimage": ""},
"15": {"questext": "What notable outcome was achieved despite the Congress's rejection of the August Offer?", "options": ["For the first time, the inherent right of Indians to frame their own constitution was recognized, and the Viceroy's Executive Council was enlarged to give Indians a majority (8 out of 12) by July 1941", "The formation of a full Interim Government", "The formal declaration of Pakistan", "The launch of the Quit India Movement"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>For the first time, the inherent right of Indians to frame their own constitution was recognized, and the Viceroy's Executive Council was enlarged to give Indians a majority (8 out of 12) by July 1941.</b><br><br>Although the August Offer was rejected, for the first time the inherent right of Indians to frame their constitution was recognized, and Congress' demand for a <b>Constituent Assembly</b> was conceded. <b>Dominion status</b> was also explicitly offered.<br><br>In <b>July 1941</b>, the Viceroy's Executive Council was enlarged to give Indians a majority (<b>8 out of 12</b>), though the British retained charge of defence, finance and home. A <b>National Defence Council</b> was also set up with purely advisory functions.", "expimage": ""},
"16": {"questext": "Who was the first Satyagrahi selected to offer Individual Satyagraha, starting on 17 October 1940?", "options": ["Acharya Vinoba Bhave", "Jawaharlal Nehru", "Brahma Dutt", "Mahatma Gandhi"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Acharya Vinoba Bhave.</b><br><br>After the rejection of the August Offer, Congress launched a symbolic protest known as <b>Individual Satyagraha</b> to oppose the August proposal and prove itself separate from the war; this ideology was Gandhiji's. It began at <b>Pavnar Ashram (Maharashtra)</b>, with <b>Acharya Vinoba Bhave</b> as the first Satyagrahi (17 October 1940), followed by <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b> as the second, and <b>Brahma Dutt</b> as the third.<br><br>Also called the '<b>Dilli Chalo Movement</b>', it was meant to avoid the risk of a mass movement turning violent, keeping <b>non-violence</b> as its centrepiece. The second phase began in <b>January 1941</b>, and about <b>25,000 Satyagrahis</b> went to jail overall.", "expimage": ""},
"17": {"questext": "Which 1941 development involving Germany, Russia and Japan changed the Indian situation and eventually led to the Cripps Mission?", "options": ["Germany's attack on Russia and Japan's attack on Pearl Harbour, drawing the US into the war", "The Quit India Movement", "The Royal Indian Navy Mutiny", "Direct Action Day"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Germany's attack on Russia and Japan's attack on Pearl Harbour, drawing the US into the war.</b><br><br>The <b>German attack on Russia</b> (22 June 1941) brought Russia into the Allied Powers, while <b>Japan's attack on Pearl Harbour</b> drew the <b>US</b> into the war. Consequently, <b>Roosevelt</b> called upon <b>Churchill</b> to resolve the Indian problem, leading Churchill to announce the <b>Cripps Mission on 11 March 1942</b>.<br><br><b>Sir Stafford Cripps</b>, a left-wing Labourite, leader of the House of Commons and a member of the British War Cabinet who had actively supported the Indian national movement, was dispatched to India on 22 March 1942 with a draft declaration to negotiate with Indian leaders.", "expimage": ""},
"18": {"questext": "What did the Cripps Proposal offer regarding the status of the proposed Indian Union?", "options": ["Dominion status, with freedom to decide relations with the Commonwealth and participate in the United Nations", "Immediate and complete independence", "Continuation of direct British Crown rule", "Automatic merger with Pakistan"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Dominion status, with freedom to decide relations with the Commonwealth and participate in the United Nations.</b><br><br>Under the <b>Cripps Proposal</b>, an Indian Union with <b>dominion status</b> would be set up, free to decide its relations with the Commonwealth and to participate in the United Nations and other international bodies. After the war, a <b>Constituent Assembly</b>, partly elected by provincial assemblies through proportional representation and partly nominated by the Princes, would frame a new constitution.<br><br>The British Government would accept the new constitution subject to two conditions: any province unwilling to join the Union could form a separate union, and the constitution-making body and British Government would negotiate a treaty for the transfer of power and safeguarding minorities. During the war, defence and the Governor General's powers would remain with the British.", "expimage": ""},
"19": {"questext": "What was considered the most controversial or 'mischievous' part of the Cripps Proposal?", "options": ["That any part(s) of India not ready to adhere to the new Constitution could frame its own constitution with the same status as the rest of India", "The immediate transfer of defence to Indians", "The abolition of the princely states", "Compulsory adult franchise"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>That any part(s) of India not ready to adhere to the new Constitution could frame its own constitution with the same status as the rest of India.</b><br><br>The most mischievous part of the Cripps Proposal was that if any part(s) of India were not ready to adhere to the Constitution, they would be free to frame their own and be given the same status as the rest of India. This, along with earlier provisions, indirectly conceded the <b>League's demand for Pakistan</b> and posed a serious threat to the unity of India.", "expimage": ""},
"20": {"questext": "What did Gandhi call the Cripps Proposal after its terms were made public?", "options": ["\"A post-dated cheque on a crashing bank\"", "\"A rotten and termite-infested offer\"", "\"Dominion status is dead as a rusty door nail\"", "\"An invitation to Divide and Quit\""], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>\"A post-dated cheque on a crashing bank\".</b><br><br>Except for setting up an expanded Viceroy's Executive Council with greater Indian association, the remaining Cripps proposals were nothing more than post-war promises, made at a time when the future of the war and of Britain itself was uncertain. Gandhi therefore called the proposal a <b>\"post-dated cheque on a crashing bank\"</b>.<br><br>The Congress rejected it, demanding complete freedom rather than dominion status, while the League, though initially pleased, also rejected it once other parties had done so. The mission's failure is also attributed to behind-the-scenes sabotage by the <b>Viceroy and Secretary of State</b>, guided by <b>Churchill</b>, who wanted it only as propaganda for the Allies.", "expimage": ""},
"21": {"questext": "Which of the following was a key factor behind the launch of the Quit India Movement in 1942?", "options": ["The failure of the Cripps Mission, which revealed Britain's unchanged attitude amid a growing threat of Japanese invasion", "The success of the August Offer", "The formation of the Indian National Army", "The riots of Direct Action Day"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The failure of the Cripps Mission, which revealed Britain's unchanged attitude amid a growing threat of Japanese invasion.</b><br><br>The failure of the <b>Cripps Mission</b> and the threat of Japanese invasion brought about an immediate change in Gandhi's attitude — he believed British withdrawal would remove the invitation for Japanese invasion. Other factors included: growing popular discontent due to rising prices and shortage of commodities; fears of a British <b>scorched earth policy</b> in Assam, Bengal and Orissa; and such low popular faith in British rule that people were withdrawing deposits from banks and post offices.", "expimage": ""},
"22": {"questext": "On which date did the Congress Working Committee meet at Wardha and pass a resolution demanding complete independence, setting the stage for the Quit India Movement?", "options": ["14th July, 1942", "8th August, 1942", "9th August, 1942", "23rd March, 1940"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>14th July, 1942.</b><br><br>The Congress Working Committee met at <b>Wardha on 14th July 1942</b> and passed a resolution demanding complete independence. Gandhiji warned that if the proposal for struggle was not accepted, he would \"create a movement bigger than the Congress with the sand of the country itself.\" The following month, the <b>All India Congress Committee</b> met at Gowalia Tank (Bombay), where the proposal was approved.", "expimage": ""},
"23": {"questext": "On which date and at which venue was the Quit India Resolution ratified?", "options": ["8th August 1942, Gowalia Tank, Bombay", "14th July 1942, Wardha", "9th August 1942, Delhi", "23rd March 1940, Lahore"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>8th August 1942, Gowalia Tank, Bombay.</b><br><br>The All-India Congress Committee met at the historic grounds of <b>Gowalia Tank</b> (later renamed 'August Kranti Ground') on <b>8th August 1942</b> and ratified the Quit India Resolution, demanding an immediate end to British rule.<br><br>Key points of the resolution included: a declaration of free India's commitment to defend itself against fascism and imperialism; formation of a provisional Government of India after British withdrawal; sanction of a civil disobedience movement with <b>Gandhi named as leader</b>; and Gandhi's famous mantra of '<b>Do or Die</b>' — either India would be made free, or the struggle would continue till death rather than accept the permanence of slavery.", "expimage": ""},
"24": {"questext": "According to the instructions Gandhiji gave at Gowalia Tank, what were government servants expected to do during the Quit India Movement?", "options": ["Not leave their jobs, but declare their loyalty to the Congress", "Resign from their jobs immediately", "Join the Indian National Army", "Go underground immediately"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Not leave their jobs, but declare their loyalty to the Congress.</b><br><br>Gandhiji's instructions, announced at Gwalia Tank, specified that: <b>government servants</b> should not leave their jobs but declare loyalty to Congress; <b>soldiers</b> should refuse to fire on their countrymen; <b>students</b> should leave their studies only if they could remain firm on their decision till independence was achieved; and if a landlord was pro-government, rent should not be paid to him. Kings and Maharajas were asked to cooperate with the public and accept the sovereignty of their people.", "expimage": ""},
"25": {"questext": "The mass arrest of Congress leaders, including Gandhi and Nehru, on 9th August 1942 is remembered by which name?", "options": ["Operation Zero Hour", "Operation Polo", "August Kranti", "Direct Action"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Operation Zero Hour.</b><br><br>Immediately after the passage of the Bombay resolution, many leaders including Gandhi and Nehru were arrested in a massive operation known as '<b>Operation Zero Hour</b>' on 9th August 1942. Gandhi was imprisoned at the <b>Aga Khan Palace</b>, while other Congress stalwarts were imprisoned at <b>Ahmednagar Fort</b>. The Congress was declared an illegal organization, its offices sealed and bank accounts frozen.<br><br><b>Sarojini Naidu</b> and <b>Kasturba Gandhi</b> were also arrested and kept at the Aga Khan Palace. <b>Dr. Rajendra Prasad</b> was put under house arrest at Bankipur Jail, Patna, while <b>Jai Prakash Narayan</b>, arrested and held at Hazaribagh Central Jail, later escaped and formed the underground group '<b>Azad Dasta</b>'.", "expimage": ""},
"26": {"questext": "The most violent phase of the Quit India Movement (9th-15th August 1942), remembered as the 'Great August Revolt', was predominantly of what character?", "options": ["Urban, with violent protests in Delhi, Mumbai, Pune and Ahmedabad", "Rural, centred in Bengal villages", "Naval, centred in Bombay harbour", "Tribal, centred in Odisha"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Urban, with violent protests in Delhi, Mumbai, Pune and Ahmedabad.</b><br><br>Stage-I of the Quit India Movement, remembered as the '<b>Great August Revolt</b>', lasted from 9th to 15th August 1942 and was predominantly urban, with violent protests in <b>Delhi, Mumbai, Pune, Ahmedabad</b>, etc., where protestors attacked rails, telegraph and postal services — events resembling the <b>Revolt of 1857</b>.<br><br>Factories shut down due to strikes in Ahmedabad, Madras, Bangalore and Saharanpur, and communication lines, police stations and government buildings were attacked. The movement had its greatest impact in <b>Bengal, Bihar, the United Provinces, Madras and Bombay</b>, though participation was seen throughout India.", "expimage": ""},
"27": {"questext": "Under whose leadership was the first parallel government of the Quit India Movement formed at Ballia in August 1942?", "options": ["Chittu Pandey", "Y.B. Chavan", "Nana Patil", "Usha Mehta"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Chittu Pandey.</b><br><br>In Stage-II of the movement (August–September 1942), the centre shifted to rural areas as young leaders, in the absence of top leadership, moved towards the countryside. Under Congress leader <b>Chittu Pandey</b>, <b>Ballia</b> saw the <b>first parallel government</b> formed during the movement, lasting for about a week in August 1942. Parallel governments were also established at <b>Tamluk, Satara</b>, and briefly at <b>Talcher (Odisha)</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"28": {"questext": "The 'Prati Sarkar' parallel government, organized by leaders like Y.B. Chavan and Nana Patil, was formed at which location?", "options": ["Satara (mid-1943 to 1945)", "Tamluk (Midnapore)", "Ballia", "Talcher"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Satara (mid-1943 to 1945).</b><br><br>At <b>Satara</b>, the parallel government named '<b>Prati Sarkar</b>' was organized under leaders like <b>Y.B. Chavan</b> and <b>Nana Patil</b>. It organized village libraries and <b>Nyayadan Mandalas</b>, carried out prohibition campaigns, and arranged 'Gandhi marriages' to which scheduled castes were invited — making it the <b>longest surviving</b> parallel government of the movement.<br><br>At <b>Tamluk (Midnapore, December 1942 – September 1944)</b>, the '<b>Jatiya Sarkar</b>' (National Government) undertook cyclone relief work, sanctioned school grants, and organized Bidyut Bahinis.", "expimage": ""},
"29": {"questext": "Who started the first underground radio station in Bombay during the Quit India Movement?", "options": ["Usha Mehta", "Aruna Asaf Ali", "Sucheta Kriplani", "Biju Patnaik"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Usha Mehta.</b><br><br>Stage-III of the movement (October–December 1942) was marked by underground activities carried out by young leaders such as <b>Ram Manohar Lohia, Jayaprakash Narayan, Aruna Asaf Ali, Usha Sharma, Biju Patnaik, Chhotubhai Puranik, Achyut Patwardhan, Sucheta Kriplani</b> and <b>R.P. Goenka</b>, limited to attacks by educated youth on police, army and communication installations.<br><br><b>Usha Mehta</b> started an underground radio station in Bombay — the first of its kind in the movement. Underground leaders, part of the '<b>Bomb Gola</b>', also collected materials like gunpowder for distribution among secret organisations.", "expimage": ""},
"30": {"questext": "Gandhiji's 21-day fast at the Aga Khan Palace, protesting the repressive action against the Quit India Movement, began in which month?", "options": ["February 1943", "March 1940", "August 1942", "May 1944"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>February 1943.</b><br><br>Gandhiji announced a <b>21-day fast in February 1943</b> at the Aga Khan Palace against the repressive action taken against the movement. The demand for his release intensified from within the country and abroad. Royalists <b>M.S. Aney, N.R. Sarkar</b> and <b>H.P. Modi</b> resigned from the Viceroy's Executive in protest.<br><br>Gandhiji withdrew his fast on <b>7 March 1943</b>. Due to his poor health, the government released him from imprisonment on <b>6 May 1944</b>. Notably, before his release, his wife <b>Kasturba Gandhi</b> and personal secretary <b>Mahadev Desai</b> had died.", "expimage": ""},
"31": {"questext": "Which social groups formed the core participants of the Quit India Movement, according to its social base?", "options": ["Students, women, workers and peasants across various strata", "Only the urban elite", "Exclusively cadre of the Muslim League", "Only officials of the princely states"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Students, women, workers and peasants across various strata.</b><br><br>Youth, especially school and college students, remained at the forefront, while women — prominently <b>Aruna Asaf Ali, Sucheta Kriplani</b> and <b>Usha Mehta</b> — actively participated. Workers went on strike facing repression, and <b>peasants of all strata</b> were at the heart of the movement, concentrating their offensive on symbols of authority with a complete absence of anti-zamindari violence; some zamindars even participated.<br><br>Lower-level government officials also participated, eroding government loyalty. <b>Communists</b>, though officially boycotting the movement, participated locally in hundreds. The contribution of <b>Muslims</b> was doubtful, though some sheltered underground activists, and there were no communal clashes. <b>Princely States</b> showed a low-key response.", "expimage": ""},
"32": {"questext": "How did the Muslim League react to the Quit India Movement?", "options": ["It condemned the movement and urged Muslims neither to support nor participate, later giving the slogan 'Divide and Quit'", "It actively joined and led the movement", "It remained entirely silent without any statement", "It fully supported the movement alongside the Congress"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>It condemned the movement and urged Muslims neither to support nor participate, later giving the slogan 'Divide and Quit'.</b><br><br>The <b>Muslim League</b> condemned the Quit India Movement and called upon Indian Muslims neither to support nor participate in it. On <b>23 March 1943</b>, it called for celebrating 'Pakistan Day', and in <b>December 1943</b>, at its convention in <b>Karachi</b>, the League gave the slogan '<b>Divide and Quit</b>'.", "expimage": ""},
"33": {"questext": "What was the Communist Party of India's stance on the Quit India Movement?", "options": ["It opposed the movement, believing the war against Nazism was more important than the freedom struggle", "It fully supported and organised the movement", "It remained entirely neutral", "It joined the Muslim League in condemning it"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>It opposed the movement, believing the war against Nazism was more important than the freedom struggle.</b><br><br>The <b>CPI</b>, which had earlier supported the national movement, changed its attitude once Germany attacked Russia (a British ally), and held that the war against Nazism was more important than the struggle for freedom.<br><br>The <b>Hindu Mahasabha</b> also repudiated the Congress' policy, believing Congress should instead have focused on neutralizing the League's demand for Pakistan. Ultra-liberal leader <b>Tej Bahadur Sapru</b> considered the movement ill-considered and untimely, and <b>Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar</b> said it was \"madness to weaken law and order when the enemy is on our borders.\"", "expimage": ""},
"34": {"questext": "How is the Quit India Movement generally regarded in the context of India's freedom struggle?", "options": ["As the last people's movement and the climax of the national struggle", "As the first organised movement of the freedom struggle", "As a purely constitutional movement", "As a movement led entirely by the Muslim League"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>As the last people's movement and the climax of the national struggle.</b><br><br>The Quit India Movement was the most violent movement of the freedom struggle, with large-scale civilian casualties and around <b>900 police and military casualties</b>, with firing on <b>538 occasions</b>. The erosion of British hegemony convinced the British that their days were numbered in India, hastening the process towards freedom.<br><br>It was the only movement without a set programme or leadership, guided solely by Gandhi's call for '<b>Do or Die</b>'. It convinced the world of the urgency of India's freedom movement, with many Allied nations, including the USA, supporting Indian independence. It is regarded as the <b>last people's movement</b> and the <b>climax or culmination</b> of the national struggle.", "expimage": ""},
"35": {"questext": "Which civil service did Subhash Chandra Bose qualify for, but resign from as he did not want to wear the 'emblem of servitude'?", "options": ["Indian Civil Service (ICS)", "Indian Police Service", "Indian Foreign Service", "Royal Indian Navy"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Indian Civil Service (ICS).</b><br><br>Born in <b>1897</b>, <b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b> was deeply influenced by the cultural atmosphere of Bengal. He graduated from Calcutta University, studied philosophy at Cambridge and qualified for the <b>Indian Civil Service (ICS)</b>, but resigned as he did not want to wear the 'emblem of servitude'. He considered <b>Chittaranjan Das</b> his political guru.", "expimage": ""},
"36": {"questext": "At which Congress session did Subhash Chandra Bose defeat Pattabhi Sitaramayya (Gandhi's nominee) for the party presidency, leading to a major crisis?", "options": ["Tripuri session, 1939", "Haripura session, 1938", "Lahore session, 1929", "Faizpur session, 1937"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Tripuri session, 1939.</b><br><br>Bose was among the leaders of the left/socialist faction, along with Nehru, and was among the first to demand 'complete independence' at the <b>1928 annual session</b>. He was chosen Mayor of Calcutta from jail in <b>1932</b>, and became president of Congress at the <b>Haripura session (1938)</b>.<br><br>At the <b>Tripuri session (1939)</b>, Bose contested for another term despite Gandhi favouring Pattabhi Sitaramayya, and defeated him — a result Gandhi called his own defeat. Working Committee members resigned, making it impossible for Bose to function, and he resigned to form the '<b>Forward Bloc</b>'. Rabindranath Tagore, who regarded him as 'Deshnayak', supported him through this tension.", "expimage": ""},
"37": {"questext": "Who originally founded the Indian National Army (INA) in Singapore on 1 September 1942?", "options": ["Captain Mohan Singh", "Subhash Chandra Bose", "Rash Behari Bose", "Major Fujiwara"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Captain Mohan Singh.</b><br><br>The INA (Azad Hind Fauj) was formed outside India's borders with Japanese support. <b>Capt. Mohan Singh</b>, an officer of the British Indian Army, originally founded it in Singapore on <b>1 September 1942</b> with Japan's Indian POWs, encouraged by <b>Major Fujiwara</b> of the Japanese army. After the fall of Singapore, the surrendered Indian contingent grew to around <b>40,000</b>, and it enlisted itself into the INA.<br><br>Meanwhile, <b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b> had disappeared in January 1941, travelling via Peshawar, Russia and Berlin, where he sought Hitler's help and established the '<b>Free India Centre</b>'.", "expimage": ""},
"38": {"questext": "What two key decisions were taken at the Tokyo Conference, convened by Rash Behari Bose?", "options": ["To establish the Indian Independence League, and to raise the INA/Azad Hind Fauj to wage war for India's liberation", "To declare Pakistan Day, and to form the Forward Bloc", "To launch the Quit India Movement, and to form an Interim Government", "To hold the Shimla Conference, and to launch the Cabinet Mission"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>To establish the Indian Independence League, and to raise the INA/Azad Hind Fauj to wage war for India's liberation.</b><br><br><b>Rash Behari Bose</b>, settled in Japan, convened a conference of Indians living in South East Asia at Tokyo, known as the '<b>Tokyo Conference</b>', which took two decisions: to establish the <b>Indian Independence League</b>, and to raise the <b>INA/Azad Hind Fauj</b>. The Japanese government promised full support. The nucleus of the INA comprised Indian POWs — soldiers of the British Indian Army captured during the fall of Malaya, Singapore and Burma.", "expimage": ""},
"39": {"questext": "When did Subhash Chandra Bose form the 'Provisional Government of Free India'?", "options": ["21st October, 1943", "2nd July, 1943", "1st September, 1942", "18th August, 1945"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>21st October, 1943.</b><br><br>Bose reached Japanese-controlled <b>Singapore on 2nd July 1943</b>, where he was given command of the Indian Independence League, and was handed command of the INA in <b>July 1943</b>. On <b>21st October 1943</b>, he formed the '<b>Provisional Government of Free India</b>', which was recognized by <b>nine governments</b>, including Germany and Japan, with headquarters at Rangoon and Singapore. He gave the slogans '<b>Delhi Chalo</b>' (March to Delhi) and '<b>Give me blood and I shall give you freedom</b>'.", "expimage": ""},
"40": {"questext": "The Andaman and Nicobar Islands, handed over to Bose's Provisional Government by Japan, were renamed as?", "options": ["Shahid and Swaraj Islands", "Azad and Hind Islands", "Subhas and Nehru Islands", "Free and Forward Islands"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Shahid and Swaraj Islands.</b><br><br>Japan passed authority over the Andaman and Nicobar Islands to Bose's Provisional Government and the INA, which renamed them '<b>Shahid</b>' and '<b>Swaraj</b>' Islands — the first Indian territories with a Free Provisional Indian Government's flag flying. Bose set up a women's regiment, the '<b>Rani Jhansi Regiment</b>', with the other brigades of the Azad Hind Fauj named <b>Subhas, Nehru and Gandhi Brigades</b>.<br><br>The INA columns, supported by the Japanese army, marched towards North East India and reached <b>Kohima on 19 March 1944</b>, unfurling the flag of free India at <b>Moirang (Manipur) in April 1944</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"41": {"questext": "What sealed the fate of the INA in the final phase of the Second World War?", "options": ["The defeat of Japan after the nuclear attacks on Hiroshima and Nagasaki", "Direct Action Day", "The Royal Indian Navy Mutiny", "The Cabinet Mission Plan"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The defeat of Japan after the nuclear attacks on Hiroshima and Nagasaki.</b><br><br>The defeat of Japan following the US nuclear attacks on <b>Hiroshima and Nagasaki</b> sealed the fate of the INA. Many INA officers were arrested and sent to India for trial, but the surge in public support ensured they were not punished and were released.<br><br>On <b>18th August 1945</b>, the aircraft carrying <b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b> crashed in <b>Formosa (now Taiwan)</b>, and he was reported killed — though many refused to believe the story, and the mystery surrounding his disappearance persists.", "expimage": ""},
"42": {"questext": "Between which years were the INA (Red Fort) Trials, involving British court-martial proceedings against INA officers, held?", "options": ["November 1945 and May 1946", "August 1942 and 1943", "1939 and 1940", "1947 and 1948"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>November 1945 and May 1946.</b><br><br>The INA/Red Fort Trials refer to British court-martial proceedings against INA officers held between <b>November 1945 and May 1946</b> for charges including treason, torture, murder and abetment to murder. The first was the joint trial of <b>Shah Nawaz Khan, Prem Sahgal</b> and <b>Gurubaksh Singh Dhillon</b>, followed by trials of Abdul Rashid, Shinghara Singh, Fateh Khan and Capt. Malik Munawar Khan Awan.<br><br>The <b>INA Defence Committee</b>, formed by the Congress, included <b>Jawaharlal Nehru, Bhulabhai Desai, Kailashnath Katju, Asaf Ali</b> and <b>Tej Bahadur Sapru</b>. Though the court-martial found the accused guilty, Viceroy <b>Lord Wavell</b> pardoned them given the circumstances.", "expimage": ""},
"43": {"questext": "The C.R. Formula (1944), proposed by C. Rajagopalachari, sought to resolve the political deadlock between which two parties?", "options": ["The Indian National Congress and the Muslim League", "The Congress and the Hindu Mahasabha", "The Muslim League and the Hindu Mahasabha", "The Congress and the Communist Party of India"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The Indian National Congress and the Muslim League.</b><br><br>The <b>C.R. Formula</b> (or Rajaji formula) sought to resolve the deadlock between the <b>Muslim League</b>, which viewed Hindus and Muslims as different entities requiring separate nations, and the <b>Congress</b>, which opposed this position. In <b>1944</b>, with Gandhiji's approval, <b>C. Rajagopalachari</b> prepared this compromise formula for Congress-League cooperation.", "expimage": ""},
"44": {"questext": "According to the C.R. Formula, what would decide whether the Muslim-majority areas of North-West and North-East India would form a separate sovereign state?", "options": ["A plebiscite among the entire population of those areas, held after the war", "A decision by the Viceroy alone", "A vote in the Constituent Assembly", "A referendum restricted to League members only"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>A plebiscite among the entire population of those areas, held after the war.</b><br><br>The C.R. Formula proposed that the Muslim League endorse the Congress demand for independence and cooperate in forming a provisional government at the centre; after the war, the entire population of Muslim-majority areas in the North-West and North-East would decide by <b>plebiscite</b> whether to form a separate sovereign state. In case of partition, a joint agreement would safeguard defence, commerce and communications, and the terms would be operative only if England transferred full power to India.<br><br>Gandhi placed the formula before Jinnah, but the <b>Gandhi-Jinnah talks failed</b> after two weeks. Jinnah rejected it, saying he did not want a \"termite-infested, rotten Pakistan.\"", "expimage": ""},
"45": {"questext": "Who succeeded Lord Linlithgow as Viceroy of India in October 1943, and later proposed the Wavell Plan?", "options": ["Lord Wavell", "Lord Mountbatten", "Lord Curzon", "Lord Willingdon"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Lord Wavell.</b><br><br><b>Lord Wavell</b> replaced Linlithgow as Viceroy of India in October 1943, at a time when the situation in India was extremely tense. On <b>14 June 1945</b>, he presented the '<b>Wavell Plan</b>', proposing a new Executive Council in which, apart from the Viceroy and the Commander-in-Chief, all members would be Indians, functioning as an interim arrangement under the framework of the <b>Government of India Act, 1935</b>.<br><br>The plan proposed equal representation for Caste Hindus and Muslims, retained the Viceroy's veto on the advice of ministers, transferred the foreign affairs portfolio to an Indian member, and kept defence with a British general until the full transfer of power.", "expimage": ""},
"46": {"questext": "The Shimla Conference (25 June 1945), summoned by Wavell to discuss his plan, largely broke down over disagreement on which issue?", "options": ["The nomination of Muslim members to the proposed Executive Council", "The name 'Pakistan'", "The location of the future Constituent Assembly", "The question of dominion status"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The nomination of Muslim members to the proposed Executive Council.</b><br><br>In order to discuss the proposal, Wavell summoned a conference in <b>Shimla on 25 June 1945</b>, attended by 21 Indian political leaders, with <b>Maulana Abul Kalam Azad</b> representing the Congress and <b>Jinnah</b> representing the Muslim League.<br><br>The main area of conflict was that, instead of allowing all parties to nominate members from all communities, the plan segregated members by religion and caste. The <b>Muslim League</b> demanded to be the sole nominator of Muslim members, while the <b>Congress</b>, as a national organisation, insisted on nominating representatives from all communities.", "expimage": ""},
"47": {"questext": "When did Lord Wavell declare the Shimla Conference on his plan to be a failure?", "options": ["14 July 1945", "25 June 1945", "20 February 1947", "3 June 1947"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>14 July 1945.</b><br><br>Leaders of the Depressed Classes also insisted on separate electoral representation, and finally, on <b>14 July 1945</b>, Lord Wavell declared the conference a failure. Meanwhile, a general election in the United Kingdom in 1945 brought the <b>Labour Party</b> to power, which sent a <b>Cabinet Mission</b> to India, marking a fresh approach after the failure of the Wavell Plan. Gandhiji did not attend the conference but was present in Shimla.", "expimage": ""},
"48": {"questext": "What was the primary trigger for the Royal Indian Navy Mutiny of February 1946?", "options": ["Racial discrimination and poor food, pay and working conditions faced by the ratings", "The demand for Pakistan", "Riots of Direct Action Day", "The failure of the Cabinet Mission"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Racial discrimination and poor food, pay and working conditions faced by the ratings.</b><br><br>The <b>Royal Indian Navy Mutiny</b> (also called the Bombay Mutiny or Ratings Mutiny) began on <b>18 February 1946</b>, when <b>1,100 sailors</b> of the naval ship <b>HMIS Talwar</b> in Bombay went on strike protesting racial discrimination and poor food, faced by <b>Ratings</b> — the non-commissioned and Junior Commissioned Officers of the Royal Indian Navy. The sailors also demanded the release of <b>B.C. Dutt</b>, arrested for writing 'Quit India' on the ship's walls.", "expimage": ""},
"49": {"questext": "During the RIN Mutiny, which three flags were carried simultaneously by the rebels in their demonstrations?", "options": ["The Congress tricolour, the green flag of the Muslim League, and the flag of the CPI", "The Congress flag, the Union Jack and the Muslim League flag", "The British flag, the INA flag and the Congress flag", "The CPI flag, the Union Jack and the Akali flag"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The Congress tricolour, the green flag of the Muslim League, and the flag of the CPI.</b><br><br>The mutiny got the full support of sailors in <b>Bombay and Karachi</b>, with slogans like Inquilab Zindabad, Jai Hind, calls for Hindu-Muslim unity, and demands to release INA prisoners being raised. An unprecedented strike was organized in Bombay with large worker participation. The rebels captured certain naval ships, anchored them in Bombay Harbour, mounted guns, pulled down the Union Jack, and in their demonstrations carried the <b>Congress tricolour, the League's green flag, and the CPI flag</b> simultaneously, threatening to open fire on Bombay city.", "expimage": ""},
"50": {"questext": "Whose statement calling on the RIN mutineers to end their action was echoed by Jinnah on behalf of the Muslim League?", "options": ["Vallabhbhai Patel", "Jawaharlal Nehru", "Mahatma Gandhi", "Lord Wavell"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Vallabhbhai Patel.</b><br><br><b>Patel</b> issued a statement calling on the strikers to end their action, which was echoed by a statement from <b>Mohammed Ali Jinnah</b> in Calcutta on behalf of the Muslim League. The rebels finally surrendered, saying, \"We are surrendering to India, not to Britain.\"<br><br>On the second day of the mutiny, British PM <b>Clement Attlee</b> announced the appointment and dispatch of the <b>Cabinet Mission</b> to resolve the Indian problem, reportedly hurried under the pressure of the RIN Mutiny.", "expimage": ""},
"51": {"questext": "In the elections to the Central Legislature held between December 1945 and January 1946, how many of the 102 elected seats did the Congress win?", "options": ["59", "43", "73", "8"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>59.</b><br><br>On 19 September 1945, Viceroy <b>Lord Wavell</b> announced elections to the central and provincial legislatures. In the central elections, the <b>Indian National Congress</b> emerged as the largest party, winning <b>59 of 102 elected seats</b>. The <b>Muslim League</b> won all Muslim constituencies but failed to win any other seats. Of the remaining 13 seats, 8 went to Europeans, 3 to independents and 2 to Akali candidates in the Sikh constituencies of Punjab.", "expimage": ""},
"52": {"questext": "In the 1946 Provincial Elections, out of a total of 1585 seats, what percentage of seats did the Congress win?", "options": ["58.23%", "26.81%", "45%", "33.33%"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>58.23%.</b><br><br>In the <b>Provincial Elections of 1946</b>, the Congress won <b>923 seats (58.23%)</b> of the total 1585 seats, while the All-India Muslim League won <b>425 seats (26.81%)</b>, placing it second.<br><br>The Congress formed ministries in Assam, Bihar, Bombay, Central Provinces, Madras, NWFP, Orissa and the United Provinces, while the Muslim League formed ministries in <b>Bengal and Sind</b>, and a coalition of Congress, the Unionist Party and the Akalis was formed in <b>Punjab</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"53": {"questext": "Who were the three members of the Cabinet Mission sent to India in 1946?", "options": ["Lord Pethick-Lawrence, Sir Stafford Cripps and A.V. Alexander", "Lord Wavell, Lord Linlithgow and Lord Mountbatten", "Jinnah, Nehru and Gandhi", "Attlee, Churchill and Cripps"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Lord Pethick-Lawrence, Sir Stafford Cripps and A.V. Alexander.</b><br><br>At the initiative of <b>Clement Attlee</b>, the British Prime Minister, a mission consisting of <b>Lord Pethick-Lawrence</b> (Secretary of State for India), <b>Sir Stafford Cripps</b> (President of the Board of Trade), and <b>A.V. Alexander</b> (First Lord of the Admiralty) was sent to India in February 1946, arriving on <b>24 March 1946</b>.<br><br>Pethick-Lawrence stated the objective was to prepare a procedure for framing a constitution and to arrange for an interim government. The Mission held talks with the Congress and the League and, unable to reach an agreed formula, published its own proposals in the State Paper on <b>16 May 1946</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"54": {"questext": "The Cabinet Mission Plan rejected the demand for a full-fledged Pakistan and instead proposed a Union of India that would deal with which subjects?", "options": ["Foreign Affairs, Defence and Communications", "Education, Health and Agriculture", "Finance, Commerce and Railways", "Home Affairs, Police and Judiciary"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Foreign Affairs, Defence and Communications.</b><br><br>The Cabinet Mission Plan proposed the formation of a <b>Union of India</b>, including both British Indian provinces and Indian States, dealing with <b>Foreign Affairs, Defence and Communications</b>, with all other provinces enjoying full autonomy and residual powers.", "expimage": ""},
"55": {"questext": "How many total members was the Constituent Assembly, as proposed under the Cabinet Mission Plan, to consist of?", "options": ["389", "296", "292", "93"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>389.</b><br><br>The Constituent Assembly was to consist of <b>389 members</b>, with <b>292</b> sent by provincial assemblies, <b>4</b> from Chief Commissioner's provinces, and <b>93</b> nominated by princely states. Representatives of British Indian Provinces were to be elected by proportional representation via a single transferable vote.<br><br>Provinces were divided into Groups A, B and C: Group A (Hindu-majority — Madras, Bombay, Central Province, United Province, Bihar and Orissa, plus Delhi, Ajmer-Marwar, Coorg), Group B (Muslim-majority — Punjab, Sindh, North-Western Region, and Baluchistan) and Group C (Bengal and Assam). The system adopted was indirect election of one member per 10 lakh population, rejecting the adult franchise system.", "expimage": ""},
"56": {"questext": "What was the function of the Advisory Committee proposed under the Cabinet Mission Plan?", "options": ["To report to the Constituent Assembly on Fundamental Rights, Minority protection and Tribal/Excluded Areas administration", "To draft the Mountbatten Plan", "To negotiate Direct Action Day", "To oversee the RIN Mutiny trial"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>To report to the Constituent Assembly on Fundamental Rights, Minority protection and Tribal/Excluded Areas administration.</b><br><br>The <b>Advisory Committee</b> on the rights of citizens, minorities and tribal areas was required to report to the Constituent Assembly on the list of <b>Fundamental Rights</b>, clauses for the protection of minorities, and a scheme for administering Tribal and Excluded Areas. The Cabinet Mission also proposed formation of an <b>interim government</b>, and gave India the option to come out of membership of the <b>Commonwealth of Nations</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"57": {"questext": "When did the Viceroy invite 14 members to join the Interim Government following the Cabinet Mission Plan?", "options": ["15th June, 1946", "2nd September, 1946", "29th July, 1946", "9th December, 1946"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>15th June, 1946.</b><br><br>Though the Congress Working Committee did not officially accept the plan, it decided that Congress should join the proposed Constituent Assembly. Following consultations, the Viceroy invited <b>14 men</b> to join the '<b>Interim Government</b>' on 15th June 1946. The Congress proposed <b>Zakir Hussain</b> among its quota of 5 nominees. Objecting to this, on <b>29th July 1946</b>, Jinnah announced that his party would not participate in the process of forming the Constituent Assembly.", "expimage": ""},
"58": {"questext": "In the July 1946 elections to the Constituent Assembly, out of the 296 seats allotted to British Provinces and Chief Commissioners' Provinces, how many did the Congress win?", "options": ["208", "73", "78", "296"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>208.</b><br><br>The Congress won <b>208 of 296 seats</b> in the July 1946 elections. Of the 78 Muslim seats, <b>73</b> were secured by the Muslim League, three by Congress, one by the Krishak Praja Party of Bengal, and one by the Punjab Unionist Party.<br><br>Under the impression that Congress would dominate the Constituent Assembly, the <b>League withdrew its support</b> for the Cabinet Mission Plan and resolved on '<b>Direct Action</b>' on 16 August 1946 to achieve its goal of Pakistan.", "expimage": ""},
"59": {"questext": "'Direct Action Day', announced by Jinnah, was observed on 16 August 1946 and triggered massive riots in which city?", "options": ["Calcutta", "Delhi", "Bombay", "Lahore"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Calcutta.</b><br><br>In July 1946, Jinnah proclaimed that the Muslim League was 'preparing to launch a struggle', and later announced that <b>16th August 1946</b> would be '<b>Direct Action Day</b>' for winning a separate Muslim state, and boycotted the Constituent Assembly. This triggered massive riots in <b>Calcutta</b>, which spread further to <b>Noakhali, Bihar, United Provinces, Punjab</b> and the NWFP.<br><br>Gandhiji went to Noakhali to restore peace, and Mountbatten later gave him the title of '<b>One Man Boundary Force</b>' for his efforts.", "expimage": ""},
"60": {"questext": "Who was elected as the permanent President of the Constituent Assembly in its second meeting on 11 December 1946?", "options": ["Dr. Rajendra Prasad", "Sachchidanand Sinha", "Dr. B.R. Ambedkar", "Jawaharlal Nehru"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Dr. Rajendra Prasad.</b><br><br>The first meeting of the Constituent Assembly was held in Delhi on <b>9 December 1946</b>, with <b>Sachchidanand Sinha</b> as temporary President. In the second meeting on <b>11 December</b>, <b>Dr. Rajendra Prasad</b> was made the permanent President, while <b>Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar</b> was made Chairman of the Drafting Committee. The Indian Constitution was thus prepared in 2 years, 11 months and 18 days.", "expimage": ""},
"61": {"questext": "When was the Interim Government formed, with Jawaharlal Nehru taking oath of office?", "options": ["2nd September, 1946", "13th October, 1946", "9th December, 1946", "15th August, 1947"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>2nd September, 1946.</b><br><br>On <b>2 September 1946</b>, the Interim Government was formed with Pt. Nehru taking oath of office with a 12-member cabinet, which included 3 Muslim members not belonging to the League, with the door kept open for the League's 5 nominees. After great persuasion, <b>Jinnah decided to enter the Interim Government on 13 October 1946</b>, with the League nominating Liaquat Ali Khan, Raja Ghaznafar Ali Khan, Abdur Rab Nishtar, Chundrigar and Jogindra Nath Mandal.<br><br>The first meeting of the Constituent Assembly, held in Delhi on <b>9 December 1946</b>, was boycotted by the Muslim League.", "expimage": ""},
"62": {"questext": "In the Interim Cabinet, who held the portfolio of Home, Information and Broadcasting?", "options": ["Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel", "Jawaharlal Nehru", "Dr. Rajendra Prasad", "Liaquat Ali Khan"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel.</b><br><br>In the Interim Cabinet, <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b> held Commonwealth Relations and Foreign Affairs, while <b>Vallabhbhai Patel</b> held <b>Home, Information and Broadcasting</b>. Other members included Baldev Singh (Defence), John Matthai (Industry and Civil Supplies), C. Rajagopalachari (Education and Arts), C.H. Bhabha (Works, Food and Energy), Dr. Rajendra Prasad (Food and Agriculture), Asaf Ali (Railways and Transport), and Jagjivan Ram (Labour).<br><br>The League's nominees held: <b>Liaquat Ali Khan</b> (Finance), I.I. Chundrigar (Commerce), Jogendranath Mandal, Ghazanfar Ali Khan (Health) and Abdur-Rab-Nishtar (Post and Air).", "expimage": ""},
"63": {"questext": "On 20 February 1947, Clement Attlee declared that Britain would transfer power to India not later than which date?", "options": ["June 1948", "August 1947", "December 1947", "June 1947"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>June 1948.</b><br><br>The British Prime Minister <b>Clement Attlee</b> declared on <b>20 February 1947</b>, in the House of Commons, that the British would quit India after transferring power into responsible hands not later than <b>June 1948</b>, so that Indians could settle their issues before then. He also announced the appointment of <b>Lord Mountbatten</b> as Viceroy in place of Lord Wavell, who arrived as the <b>34th and last British Governor-General</b> in India.", "expimage": ""},
"64": {"questext": "The Dickie Bird Plan (Balkan Plan), the brainchild of Lord Mountbatten, was abandoned mainly due to strong opposition from whom?", "options": ["Jawaharlal Nehru", "Mahatma Gandhi", "Vallabhbhai Patel", "M.A. Jinnah"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Jawaharlal Nehru.</b><br><br>The <b>Dickie Bird Plan</b>, also known as the '<b>Balkan Plan</b>', ran the risk of balkanisation of India, involving the transfer of power to separate provinces, with Punjab and Bengal given the option to vote for partition, and princely states given the option of joining India, Pakistan, or remaining separate. It was abandoned quickly after staunch opposition by <b>Nehru</b>.<br><br>The plan was prepared by a committee of Sir Hastings (Ismay), Sir George Abell and Lord Mountbatten, and was presented by Hastings Ismay to the assembly of provincial governors in Delhi — hence also called the '<b>Isma Plan</b>'.", "expimage": ""},
"65": {"questext": "When did Lord Mountbatten announce his plan, accepting the partition of India as the final solution?", "options": ["3 June 1947", "24 March 1947", "20 February 1947", "18 July 1947"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>3 June 1947.</b><br><br><b>Lord Mountbatten</b> arrived in India on 22 March 1947, was sworn in on <b>24 March 1947</b>, and held a series of meetings with Gandhi, Nehru and Jinnah before proceeding to England in May 1947. After about two months of talks, he concluded that partition was the only option, got approval from Attlee, and secured consent from the Congress, Jinnah and the Sikh leaders before announcing his plan on <b>3 June 1947</b>, thus officially accepting partition.", "expimage": ""},
"66": {"questext": "Who among the following strongly opposed the partition of India till the end, saying it would happen only 'over my dead body'?", "options": ["Mahatma Gandhi", "Jawaharlal Nehru", "Vallabhbhai Patel", "Dr. Rajendra Prasad"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Mahatma Gandhi.</b><br><br>Under compulsion from within Congress, <b>Nehru and Patel</b> accepted the partition plan, but <b>Gandhiji</b> strongly opposed it till the end, saying, \"Even if the whole of India is engulfed in flames, Pakistan will still not be formed... it will be over my dead body.\" Tired of the League's conduct during the interim government, <b>Patel</b> remarked, \"Whether Jinnah wants partition or not, we ourselves want partition now.\"<br><br><b>Khan Abdul Ghaffar Khan</b> (Frontier Gandhi) expressed indignation, saying the Congress leadership had thrown his movement to the wolves. Ultimately, Nehru, Pant, Kripalani and Gandhiji all accepted the partition.", "expimage": ""},
"67": {"questext": "Under the Mountbatten Plan, how were the Legislative Assemblies of Bengal and Punjab to decide on the question of partition?", "options": ["Each was to meet in two parts (Muslim-majority districts and the rest) and decide by simple majority", "By a nationwide referendum", "By decision of the Viceroy alone", "By vote of the princely states"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Each was to meet in two parts (Muslim-majority districts and the rest) and decide by simple majority.</b><br><br>Under the Mountbatten Plan (also called the '<b>3 June Plan</b>'), if partition was decided, two Dominions and two Constituent Assemblies would be created. The Muslim-majority district of <b>Sylhet</b> in Assam was to decide by referendum whether to join East Bengal (Pakistan); a referendum was to be held in <b>NWFP</b> to decide between India and Pakistan; and <b>Baluchistan</b> was given the right to decide. Princely states would join either India or Pakistan, and an independent <b>Boundary Commission</b> would demarcate the divided provinces, which could later leave the Commonwealth if desired.", "expimage": ""},
"68": {"questext": "The Legislative Assembly of Sindh voted to join Pakistan on which date?", "options": ["26th June, 1947", "20th June, 1947", "29th June, 1947", "6th July, 1947"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>26th June, 1947.</b><br><br>In implementing the Mountbatten Plan, the Hindu members of the Bengal Assembly voted for partition on <b>20 June 1947</b>, and those of Punjab did the same three days later. The Legislative Assembly of <b>Sindh voted for Pakistan on 26 June 1947</b>. Sylhet's residents chose to join East Bengal, and the NWFP referendum (6–17 July, boycotted by Congress) resulted in a vote for Pakistan. <b>Baluchistan</b> also decided to join Pakistan on <b>29 June 1947</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"69": {"questext": "The Indian Independence Act, 1947, received royal assent on which date?", "options": ["18th July, 1947", "15th August, 1947", "3rd June, 1947", "20th February, 1947"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>18th July, 1947.</b><br><br>The <b>Indian Independence Act, 1947</b> received royal assent on <b>18 July 1947</b>, partitioning British India into the two dominions of <b>India (15 August)</b> and <b>Pakistan (14 August)</b>, approving the Mountbatten Plan of 3 June.<br><br>Its key provisions included: partition of Bengal and Punjab; establishment of the office of Governor-General in each country; conferring complete legislative authority on the respective Constituent Assemblies; termination of British suzerainty over Princely States from 15 August 1947, with recognition of their right to accede to either dominion; abolition of the title 'Emperor of India'; and administration under the <b>Government of India Act, 1935</b> until new constitutions were framed.", "expimage": ""},
"70": {"questext": "Who became the first Prime Minister of Pakistan upon independence?", "options": ["Liaquat Ali Khan", "Muhammad Ali Jinnah", "Jogendranath Mandal", "I.I. Chundrigar"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Liaquat Ali Khan.</b><br><br>On attaining independence, <b>Lord Mountbatten</b>, the last Viceroy, was asked by Indian leaders to continue as Governor-General of India. <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b> became India's Prime Minister on 15 August 1947, with <b>Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel</b> as Home Minister. Meanwhile, <b>Muhammad Ali Jinnah</b> became Governor-General of Pakistan, and <b>Liaquat Ali Khan</b> became Pakistan's first Prime Minister.", "expimage": ""},
"71": {"questext": "Who is credited with the wise and diplomatic integration of most of the princely states into the Indian Union?", "options": ["Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel", "Jawaharlal Nehru", "Lord Mountbatten", "Dr. Rajendra Prasad"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel.</b><br><br>The integration of princely states was solved wisely by <b>Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel</b>, using diplomacy, military force and fear of mass movement; some states signed the <b>Instrument of Accession</b>. By 15 August 1947, almost all princely states had joined the Indian Union, except <b>Junagadh, Hyderabad</b> and <b>Jammu and Kashmir</b>, which tried to maintain independence.", "expimage": ""},
"72": {"questext": "The Nawab of Junagadh initially declared the merger of his state with which country, before a referendum led to it joining India?", "options": ["Pakistan", "Nepal", "It remained fully independent", "Afghanistan"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Pakistan.</b><br><br><b>Junagadh</b>, a small state on the coast of Saurashtra surrounded by Indian territory, saw its Nawab declare merger with <b>Pakistan</b> on 15 August 1947. However, the mostly Hindu population started a mass movement for merger with India, forcing the Nawab to flee. <b>Diwan Shahnawaz Bhutto</b> invited the Indian Government to intervene, and in <b>February 1948</b>, a referendum favoured India, resulting in Junagadh's merger with India.", "expimage": ""},
"73": {"questext": "Under what codename did the Indian Army enter Hyderabad on 13 September 1948, leading to the Nizam's surrender?", "options": ["Operation Polo (also called Caterpillar)", "Operation Zero Hour", "Operation Vijay", "Operation Shakti"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Operation Polo (also called Caterpillar).</b><br><br>Hyderabad, the largest princely state, saw its Nizam sign a status quo agreement with India in <b>November 1947</b>. After a local movement against him, the Indian Army entered under '<b>Operation Polo</b>' (or 'Caterpillar') on <b>13 September 1948</b>. The Nizam surrendered and formally accepted merger with the Indian Union in <b>November 1948</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"74": {"questext": "On what date did Maharaja Hari Singh sign the Instrument of Accession, merging Jammu and Kashmir with India?", "options": ["26th October, 1947", "22nd October, 1947", "30th December, 1947", "1951"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>26th October, 1947.</b><br><br>Jammu and Kashmir, ruled by a Hindu ruler over a majority-Muslim population and bordering both India and Pakistan, saw its ruler <b>Hari Singh</b> initially wish to remain independent. After <b>Pathan tribesmen</b>, led by Pakistani military officers, infiltrated Kashmir on <b>22 October 1947</b>, Hari Singh signed the merger document with India on <b>26 October 1947</b>, following which the Indian army drove out the tribesmen.<br><br>On 30 December 1947, on Mountbatten's advice, the government referred the issue to the <b>UN Security Council</b>. A 1951 UN resolution called for a plebiscite after Pakistani troop withdrawal from POK, but this failed as <b>Pakistan refused to withdraw</b> its troops.", "expimage": ""},
"75": {"questext": "India obtained practical control of the French settlements (Chandannagar, Pondicherry, Karaikal, Mahe) on which date?", "options": ["1 November 1954", "19 December 1961", "1 November 1956", "1962"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>1 November 1954.</b><br><br>Due to their geographical location, separate referendums were held in India's French settlements, and India got practical control on <b>1 November 1954</b>. A merger treaty was signed between India and France in 1956, and when it was ratified by the French Parliament in <b>1962</b>, India also secured legal rights over these areas.", "expimage": ""},
"76": {"questext": "When did the Indian Army enter Goa, forcing the Portuguese Governor-General to surrender?", "options": ["December 1961", "July 1954", "November 1954", "1987"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>December 1961.</b><br><br>Portugal held Daman and Diu, Dadra and Nagar Haveli, and Goa, and was unwilling to give up its colonies. In <b>July 1954</b>, public resentment led to the overthrow of Portuguese rule in Dadra and Nagar Haveli. In <b>December 1961</b>, the Indian Army entered Goa and forced the Portuguese Governor-General to surrender, after which Daman and Diu also came under Indian jurisdiction. These territories were made Union Territories, with Goa becoming an independent state in <b>1987</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"77": {"questext": "Which newspaper, published by James Augustus Hicky in 1780, was the first newspaper in India (also known as The Calcutta General Advertiser)?", "options": ["Bengal Gazette", "Calcutta Gazette", "Bengal Journal", "Digdarshan"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Bengal Gazette.</b><br><br>The East India Company established its first press in <b>1684</b> at Bombay. The <b>Bengal Gazette</b>, also known as 'The Calcutta General Advertiser', was published by <b>James Augustus Hicky in 1780</b>. It was followed by <b>The Calcutta Gazette (1784)</b> and <b>The Bengal Journal (1785)</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"78": {"questext": "Who published 'Udant Martand', the first Hindi newspaper in India, in 1826?", "options": ["Pandit Jugal Kishore", "Gangadhar Bhattacharya", "James Augustus Hicky", "John Clark Marshman"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Pandit Jugal Kishore.</b><br><br>The first English newspaper in India to be published by an Indian was brought out by <b>Gangadhar Bhattacharya in 1816</b>. The first newspaper in <b>Hindi</b>, '<b>Udant Martand</b>', was published by <b>Pandit Jugal Kishore</b> at Calcutta in 1826.", "expimage": ""},
"79": {"questext": "The monthly Bangla-language magazine 'Digdarshan', begun in 1818, was started by whom?", "options": ["John Clark Marshman", "Dadabhai Naoroji", "Ishwarchandra Vidyasagar", "Harish Chandra Mukherjee"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>John Clark Marshman.</b><br><br>In <b>1818</b>, <b>John Clark Marshman</b> began publication of '<b>Digdarshan</b>', a monthly magazine in the Bangla language.", "expimage": ""},
"80": {"questext": "The Gujarati-language publication 'Raft Goftar', started in 1851, was edited under the leadership of whom?", "options": ["Dadabhai Naoroji", "Bal Gangadhar Tilak", "Surendranath Banerjee", "Motilal Ghosh"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Dadabhai Naoroji.</b><br><br>From <b>1851</b>, '<b>Raft Goftar</b>' was published under the editorial leadership of <b>Dadabhai Naoroji</b> in the <b>Gujarati</b> language. Other famous journals included the <b>Hindu Patriot</b> by Harish Chandra Mukherjee, <b>Amrit Bazar Patrika</b> by Shishir Kumar Ghosh and Motilal Ghosh, and <b>Som Prakash</b> by Ishwarchandra Vidyasagar (started 1859, in Bengali).", "expimage": ""},
"81": {"questext": "Which newspaper, founded by Bal Gangadhar Tilak in 1881 at Bombay, was published in both English and Marathi?", "options": ["Maratha and Kesari", "Hindu", "Bengali", "Common Weal"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Maratha and Kesari.</b><br><br><b>Maratha and Kesari</b> were founded by <b>Bal Gangadhar Tilak</b> in <b>1881</b> at Bombay, published in English and Marathi respectively. Other notable newspapers included: <b>Amrit Bazar Patrika</b> (Bangla, 1868, Calcutta); <b>Som Prakash</b> (Bangla, 1859, Calcutta); <b>Hindu</b> (English, 1878, Madras, G. Subramania Iyer); <b>Bengali</b> (English, 1879, Calcutta, Surendranath Banerjee); <b>Common Weal</b> (English, 1914, Madras, Annie Besant); and <b>Kavi Vachan Sudha</b> (Hindi, 1867, United Provinces, Bhartendu Harishchandra).", "expimage": ""},
"82": {"questext": "'Young India' and 'Navjivan', launched in 1919 at Ahmedabad, were edited by which leader?", "options": ["Mahatma Gandhi", "Jawaharlal Nehru", "Maulana Abul Kalam Azad", "Lala Hardayal"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Mahatma Gandhi.</b><br><br>'<b>Young India</b>' (English) and '<b>Nav Jeevan</b>' (Hindi/Gujarati) were launched in <b>1919 at Ahmedabad</b> by <b>Mahatma Gandhi</b>, who also brought out '<b>Harijan</b>' (Hindi/Gujarati, 1933, Poona). Other papers of the period included <b>Hindustan Times</b> (English, 1920, Delhi, K.M. Panikkar), <b>National Herald</b> (English, 1938, Delhi, Jawaharlal Nehru), the <b>Tribune</b> (English, 1877, Chandigarh, Sir Dayal Singh Majithia), <b>Al-Hilal and Al-Bilagh</b> (Urdu, 1912/1913, Calcutta, Maulana Abul Kalam Azad), <b>Comrade</b> (English, 1911, Calcutta, Maulana Mohammad Ali Jauhar), <b>Hamdard</b> (Urdu, 1913, Delhi, Mohammad Ali Jauhar), <b>Pratap Patra</b> (Hindi, 1910, Kanpur, Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi), and <b>Ghadar</b> (English/Punjabi, 1913, San Francisco, Lala Hardayal).", "expimage": ""},
"83": {"questext": "Who authored 'The Riddles of Hinduism'?", "options": ["Bhimrao Ambedkar", "Mahatma Gandhi", "Bal Gangadhar Tilak", "Dayanand Saraswati"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Bhimrao Ambedkar.</b><br><br><b>Bhimrao Ambedkar</b> authored '<b>The Riddles of Hinduism</b>' and '<b>Pakistan and Partition of India</b>'. Other notable freedom-era works include: <b>My Early Life</b> and <b>Hind Swaraj/India Home Rule</b> by <b>Mahatma Gandhi</b>; <b>Gita Rahasya</b> by <b>Bal Gangadhar Tilak</b>; <b>Satyarth Prakash</b> by <b>Dayanand Saraswati</b>; and <b>India Wins Freedom</b> by <b>Maulana Abul Kalam Azad</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"84": {"questext": "'Gitanjali' and 'Gora' were written by which author?", "options": ["Rabindranath Tagore", "Sarojini Naidu", "Bankim Chandra Chatterjee", "C.F. Andrews"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Rabindranath Tagore.</b><br><br><b>Rabindranath Tagore</b> wrote '<b>Gitanjali</b>', '<b>Gora</b>', and '<b>Crescent Moon, Post Office</b>'. Other notable works include: <b>Songs of India</b> by <b>Sarojini Naidu</b>; <b>Indian Renaissance</b> by <b>C.F. Andrews</b>; <b>Commentaries on the Koran</b> by <b>Saiyad Ahmed Khan</b>; <b>Religion and Social Reform</b> by <b>M.G. Ranade</b>; <b>Glimpses of World History</b> by <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b>; <b>Indian Unrest</b> by <b>Valentine Chirol</b>; <b>Nil Darpan</b> by <b>Dinabandhu Mitra</b>; and <b>War of Indian Independence</b> by <b>Savarkar</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"85": {"questext": "'My Experiments with Truth' was authored by whom?", "options": ["Mahatma Gandhi", "Surendranath Banerjee", "R.C. Dutt", "Subhash Chandra Bose"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Mahatma Gandhi.</b><br><br><b>Mahatma Gandhi</b> authored '<b>My Experiments with Truth</b>'. Other notable freedom-era works include: <b>India from Curzon to Nehru and After</b> by <b>Durga Das</b>; <b>Anand Math</b> by <b>Bankim Chandra Chatterjee</b>; <b>Nation in Making</b> by <b>Surendranath Banerjee</b>; <b>An Indian Diary</b> by <b>Montagu</b>; <b>Economic History of India</b> by <b>R.C. Dutt</b>; <b>Hints for Self-Culture</b> by <b>Lala Hardayal</b>; <b>Life Divine</b> by <b>Arvind (Aurobindo) Ghosh</b>; <b>Indian Struggle</b> by <b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b>; and <b>India Today</b> by <b>R. Palme Dutt</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"86": {"questext": "'Unhappy India' and 'The Bunch of Old Letters' were written respectively by whom?", "options": ["Lala Lajpat Rai and Arvind Ghosh", "Rajendra Prasad and Vijayalaxmi Pandit", "Sachindranath Sanyal and Bhagwati Charan Vohra", "Annie Besant and Dadabhai Naoroji"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Lala Lajpat Rai and Arvind Ghosh.</b><br><br>'<b>Unhappy India</b>' was written by <b>Lala Lajpat Rai</b>, and '<b>The Bunch of Old Letters</b>' by <b>Arvind (Aurobindo) Ghosh</b>. Other works include: <b>India Divided</b> by <b>Rajendra Prasad</b>; <b>Bandi Jeevan</b> by <b>Sachindranath Sanyal</b>; <b>The Philosophy of the Bomb</b> by <b>Bhagwati Charan Vohra</b>; <b>The Scope of Happiness</b> by <b>Vijayalaxmi Pandit</b>; <b>Poverty and Un-British Rule in India</b> by <b>Dadabhai Naoroji</b>; and <b>India: A Nation</b> by <b>Annie Besant</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"87": {"questext": "Who was the Governor General of India during the Woodhead Commission (1943), a Famine Commission of British India?", "options": ["Lord Wavell", "Lord Lytton", "Lord Elgin II", "Lord Curzon"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Lord Wavell.</b><br><br>Among the Famine Commissions in British India: the <b>Campbell Commission (1866)</b> was under Governor General <b>John Lawrence</b>; the <b>Strachey Commission (1880)</b> under <b>Lytton</b>; the <b>Lyall Commission (1897-98)</b> under <b>Elgin II</b>; the <b>MacDonnell Commission (1900)</b> under <b>Curzon</b>; and the <b>Woodhead Commission (1943)</b> under <b>Wavell</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"88": {"questext": "At which venue was the first session of the Indian National Congress held in 1885, with W.C. Banerjee presiding?", "options": ["Gokuldas Tejpal Sanskrit College, Bombay", "Calcutta", "Madras", "Allahabad"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Gokuldas Tejpal Sanskrit College, Bombay.</b><br><br>The first Congress session was held at <b>Gokuldas Tejpal Sanskrit College, Gowalia Tank, Bombay</b> in <b>1885</b>, presided by <b>W.C. Banerjee</b>, with <b>72 delegates</b> attending. It was initially named 'Indian National Union', renamed to '<b>Indian National Congress</b>' on Dadabhai Naoroji's suggestion.<br><br>The <b>1886 Calcutta</b> session (Dadabhai Naoroji) saw the National Association Conference merge with the Congress, and Viceroy Lord Dufferin's garden party invitation. The <b>1887 Madras</b> session, presided by <b>Badruddin Tayyabji</b>, marked the <b>first Muslim President</b>. The <b>1888 Allahabad</b> session, under <b>George Yule</b>, saw the first European elected President, and Lala Lajpat Rai's first Hindi speech at Congress.", "expimage": ""},
"89": {"questext": "At the 1890 Calcutta session, presided by Firozshah Mehta, who became the first woman graduate of Calcutta University to address the Congress?", "options": ["Kadambini Ganguly", "Sarojini Naidu", "Annie Besant", "Aruna Asaf Ali"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Kadambini Ganguly.</b><br><br>At the <b>1890 Calcutta</b> session, presided by <b>Firozshah Mehta</b>, <b>Kadambini Ganguly</b>, the first woman graduate of Calcutta University, addressed the Congress. The <b>1889 Bombay</b> session was presided by <b>William Wedderburn</b>, and at the <b>1896 Calcutta</b> session (Rahmatullah M. Sayani), '<b>Vande Mataram</b>' was sung for the first time.", "expimage": ""},
"90": {"questext": "At which INC session did Dadabhai Naoroji use the word 'Swaraj' for the first time from the Congress platform?", "options": ["1906, Calcutta", "1901, Calcutta", "1905, Banaras", "1907, Surat"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>1906, Calcutta.</b><br><br>At the <b>1906 Calcutta</b> session, <b>Dadabhai Naoroji</b> used the word '<b>Swaraj</b>' (self-governance) for the first time from the Congress platform, and four resolutions were adopted on Swaraj, the Boycott Movement, Swadeshi and National Education.<br><br>At the <b>1901 Calcutta</b> session (Dinshaw E. Wacha), <b>Gandhiji first appeared on the Congress platform</b>. At the <b>1905 Banaras</b> session (Gopal Krishna Gokhale), there was criticism of the Partition of Bengal and support for Swadeshi and boycott.", "expimage": ""},
"91": {"questext": "The 1907 Surat session of the Congress, presided by Rashbehari Ghosh, is notable for which event?", "options": ["The first split of the Congress between Moderates and Extremists", "The first singing of 'Jana Gana Mana'", "Lord Willingdon's attendance", "Adoption of the Poorna Swaraj resolution"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The first split of the Congress between Moderates and Extremists.</b><br><br>The <b>1907 Surat</b> session, presided by <b>Rashbehari Ghosh</b>, saw the first split of the Congress between the Moderates and Extremists. At the <b>1911 Calcutta</b> session (Bishan Narayan Dhar), '<b>Jana Gana Mana</b>' was sung for the first time. At the <b>1915 Bombay</b> session (Satyendra Prasanna Sinha), <b>Lord Willingdon</b>, then Governor of Bombay, attended.", "expimage": ""},
"92": {"questext": "The 1916 Lucknow session, marked by the unification of Moderates and Extremists, also saw an agreement between the Congress and which party?", "options": ["Muslim League", "Hindu Mahasabha", "Forward Bloc", "Swaraj Party"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Muslim League.</b><br><br>The <b>1916 Lucknow</b> session, presided by <b>Ambika Charan Mazumdar</b>, marked the unification of the Moderate and Extremist groups, and an agreement between the <b>Congress and Muslim League</b>. Here, <b>Tilak</b> gave the slogan, \"<b>Swaraj is my birthright; I will have it.</b>\"<br><br>The <b>1917 Calcutta</b> session, presided by <b>Annie Besant</b>, marked the Congress's <b>first woman president</b>. The <b>1919 Amritsar</b> session (Motilal Nehru) saw Congress extend support to the <b>Khilafat Movement</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"93": {"questext": "At which special session (1920, Calcutta) did Mahatma Gandhi move the Non-Cooperation resolution?", "options": ["Special session under Lala Lajpat Rai", "Nagpur session under C. Vijayaraghavachariar", "Gaya session under C.R. Das", "Belgaum session under Gandhi"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>Special session under Lala Lajpat Rai.</b><br><br>At the <b>1920 Calcutta Special Session</b>, presided by <b>Lala Lajpat Rai</b>, Mahatma Gandhi moved the <b>Non-Cooperation resolution</b>. At the <b>1920 Nagpur</b> session (C. Vijayaraghavachariar), the Working Committees were reconstituted on a linguistic basis, <b>M.A. Jinnah left the INC</b>, Congress declared its first policy towards princely states, and the non-cooperation programme was approved.<br><br>At the <b>1922 Gaya</b> session (C.R. Das), <b>C.R. Das and other leaders broke away</b> from the INC and formed the <b>Swaraj Party</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"94": {"questext": "Which was the only Congress session presided over by Mahatma Gandhi himself?", "options": ["1924 Belgaum session", "1925 Kanpur session", "1929 Lahore session", "1938 Haripura session"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>1924 Belgaum session.</b><br><br>The <b>1924 Belgaum</b> session was the only Congress session presided over by <b>Mahatma Gandhi</b> himself. At the <b>1925 Kanpur</b> session, <b>Sarojini Naidu</b> became the <b>first Indian woman President</b>. The <b>1927 Madras</b> session (M.A. Ansari) saw adoption of the resolution on <b>Purna Swaraj</b>, and a resolution passed to boycott the <b>Simon Commission</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"95": {"questext": "At the 1929 Lahore session, presided by Jawaharlal Nehru, which resolution declared 26 January to be observed as Independence Day?", "options": ["The Poorna Swaraj resolution", "The 1927 Purna Swaraj resolution", "The Karachi resolution", "The Ramgarh resolution"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The Poorna Swaraj resolution.</b><br><br>At the <b>1929 Lahore</b> session, presided by <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b>, the resolution on <b>Poorna Swaraj</b> was passed, the launch of the <b>Civil Disobedience Movement</b> for complete independence was decided, and <b>26 January</b> was declared to be observed as Independence Day.<br><br>The preceding <b>1928 Calcutta</b> session (Motilal Nehru) saw the formation of the <b>All India Youth Congress</b>.", "expimage": ""},
"96": {"questext": "The 1931 Karachi session, presided by Vallabhbhai Patel, endorsed which pact and nominated Gandhi for which conference?", "options": ["The Gandhi-Irwin Pact; the second Round Table Conference", "The Lucknow Pact; the Simon Commission", "The Poona Pact; the first Round Table Conference", "The C.R. Formula; the Cripps Mission"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>The Gandhi-Irwin Pact; the second Round Table Conference.</b><br><br>The <b>1931 Karachi</b> session, presided by <b>Vallabhbhai Patel</b>, passed a resolution on <b>Fundamental Rights</b> and the National Economic Programme, endorsed the <b>Gandhi-Irwin Pact</b>, and nominated Gandhi to represent the INC at the <b>second Round Table Conference</b> in London.<br><br>The <b>1934 Bombay</b> session, presided by <b>Rajendra Prasad</b>, brought an amendment in the Constitution of Congress.", "expimage": ""},
"97": {"questext": "Which was the first Congress session to be held in a village?", "options": ["1937 Faizpur session", "1936 Lucknow session", "1938 Haripura session", "1939 Tripuri session"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>1937 Faizpur session.</b><br><br>The <b>1937 Faizpur</b> session, presided by <b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b>, was the <b>first Congress session held in a village</b>. The <b>1936 Lucknow</b> session (also presided by Nehru) saw a push towards socialist ideas, and the <b>1938 Haripura</b> session, presided by <b>Subhas Chandra Bose</b>, set up the <b>National Planning Committee</b> under Jawaharlal Nehru.", "expimage": ""},
"98": {"questext": "At the 1940 Ramgarh session, presided by Abul Kalam Azad, what was resolved regarding the Civil Disobedience Movement?", "options": ["That it be launched at an appropriate time and circumstances", "That it be launched immediately", "That it be permanently abandoned", "That it be merged into the Quit India Movement"], "correct": "1", "quesimage": "", "exptext": "<b>That it be launched at an appropriate time and circumstances.</b><br><br>At the preceding <b>1939 Tripuri</b> session (Rajendra Prasad), <b>Subhas Chandra Bose</b> was re-elected but had to resign; Rajendra Prasad was appointed in his place, and Bose subsequently formed the <b>Forward Bloc</b>. At the <b>1940 Ramgarh</b> session, presided by <b>Abul Kalam Azad</b> (who remained Congress President for 6 consecutive years), it was resolved that the Civil Disobedience Movement be launched at an appropriate time and circumstances.<br><br>During <b>1941-1945</b>, marked by the Quit India Movement, RIN Mutiny, INA trials, and constitutional negotiations (Cripps Mission, Wavell Plan, Cabinet Mission), <b>no Congress session was held</b>. The <b>1946 Meerut</b> session, presided by <b>J.B. Kripalani</b>, was the <b>last session before independence</b>; Kripalani was the President of INC at Independence.", "expimage": ""}
};
